  "text": "The proof of the main result follows a method used by Alon and Shapira in [CITATION_1] , which is based on a strengthened version of the Szemerédi Regularity Lemma (proved in [CITATION_2] ). Using this method, we prove the following theorem: Theorem 1.1. Let P be an arbitrary hereditary graph property, and ε > 0. Then there is n 1.1 (P, ε) such that for any n ≥ n 1.1 (P, ε) there is p = p 1.1 (P, ε, n) satisfying with high probability ed(n, P) ≤ E P (G(n, p)) + εn 2 [CITATION_3] Note that the value of p in (1) depends on n. Thus, some additional effort is needed in order to deduce that there is a single value of p that suits all n. Theorem 1.2. Let P be an arbitrary hereditary graph property. Then there exists p = p 1.2 (P) ∈ [0, 1], such that with high probability",
